04428nam a22006375i 9780292735538DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927355387 a10.7560/7266802doi  a(DE-B1597)588043  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aBIO0260002bisacsh04a362.7342221 aWard, Margaret E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMissing Mila, Finding Family :bAn International Adoption in the Shadow of the Salvadoran Civil War /cMargaret E. Ward. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue:Dalila’s Hammock: San Salvador, El Salvador, February 2005 -- tPart One. Our Story -- tOne. Adoption: Tegucigalpa, Honduras, May– June 1983 -- tTwo. Rediscovery: Massachusetts, August– December 1997 -- tThree. Reunion: Heredia, Costa Rica, December 1997 -- tPart Two. Their Stories -- tFour. Putting the Pieces Together, 1952– 1992 -- tInterlude. Mi fl or favorita/My Favorite Flower -- tFive. Imagining Mila: New Hampshire, Summer 2007 -- tInterlude. La Guerra verdadera/The True War -- tSix. The Disappeared Children of El Salvador -- tInterlude. My Perfect World -- tEpilogue. One Story -- tAppendix I. Abbreviations and Acronyms -- tAppendix II. Family Names -- tNotes -- tReferences and Suggested Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the spring of 1983, a North American couple who were hoping to adopt a child internationally received word that if they acted quickly, they could become the parents of a boy in an orphanage in Honduras. Layers of red tape dissolved as the American Embassy there smoothed the way for the adoption. Within a few weeks, Margaret Ward and Thomas de Witt were the parents of a toddler they named Nelson—an adorable boy whose prior life seemed as mysterious as the fact that government officials in two countries had inexplicably expedited his adoption. In Missing Mila, Finding Family, Margaret Ward tells the poignant and compelling story of this international adoption and the astonishing revelations that emerged when Nelson's birth family finally relocated him in 1997. After recounting their early years together, during which she and Tom welcomed the birth of a second son, Derek, and created a family with both boys, Ward vividly recalls the upheaval that occurred when members of Nelson's birth family contacted them and sought a reunion with the boy they knew as Roberto. She describes how their sense of family expanded to include Nelson's Central American relatives, who helped her piece together the lives of her son's birth parents and their clandestine activities as guerrillas in El Salvador's civil war. In particular, Ward develops an internal dialogue with Nelson's deceased mother Mila, an elusive figure whose life and motivations she tries to understand.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBirthparentszEl Salvador. 0aIntercountry adoptionzUnited States. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72668040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292735538423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292735538/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK